reviewText: They must have had a blast making this movie, set in the snowy mountains of Alaska during its exciting boomtown days. Complete with romance, hilarity AND and some really fabulous fist fights, North to Alaska is definitely one of John Wayne's best.Claim jumpers, love triangles and power plays keep best friends Granger and Wayne on their toes, and almost at each other's throats, and right smack in the middle of it all is a delectable French lady named Capucine. Her cap is set for Wayne, but she soon finds out he's one of the most mule-headed men in Alaska!Capucine really shines in her comically romantic role. As she employs all of her feminine wiles you will actually find yourself rooting for her! Granger and Wayne are fabulously paired up in this movie as partners, especially since they are exact opposites. This film has it all - love, laughs and lots of exciting action. A definite gold mine.
Title: N/A

reviewText: Great fun here in gold rush fevered Nome sees John Wayne as his inimitable self playing (suprise suprise) himself aka Sam McCord the man's man in gold country. A gentle comic tale sees him return to Seattle and bring back a girl for his lovesick partner played superbly by Stewart Granger. He begins to regret this trip, and task after the initial maiden he is sent to fetch has unexpectantly married whilst Granger was away panning for Gold, and he must quickly find a replacement. Add in some claim jumpers, a romantic subplot, a greedy villian and the ever present sandpaper like comic tension between the main characters, and the end result is a real treat. With an excellent supporting cast, great scenery and nothing too serious to get excited about, this is quality family viewing. The location alone precludes the usual Wayne western formula, but the action and laughs come thick and fast. A great classic. Enjoy
summary: We Go North - the rush is on!!

reviewText: The first time I began to watch NORTH TO ALASKA, I could only stomach the first five minutes or more. After that, I quickly found another video. That doesn't make any sense for someone who loves Westerns, especially ones starring John Wayne. So why would I quit? Well -- it was too funny, too slap-stick for a Western of my tastes. Imagine my surprise, when a few months later, a friend suggested I watch it with her. I hestitated, but finally acquiesced to her request. I watched not only the first five minutes, but the whole thing. I was in for a big surprise! It was an excellent Western afterall! Sure, there are parts that are comedy, but there are also parts that are nothing short of classic John Wayne Western, and you will NOT be disappointed if you purchase this wonderful flick. It will keep you coming back again and again! Go for it, pull out the credit card like the fast-draw, and fire a shot at this Western! You'll be glad you did, and you can then walk straight and tall down main street, with your head held up high just as if you beat the odds in an old wild west shootout! Bang Bang! A Happy Customer Indeed -- PS: Just went out and bought myself a pair of high Sonora Western boots now! Next item on my shopping list? A good Stetson Western hat!!! Hi-Ho Silver!!!

reviewText: John Wayne did a few really good comedy westerns, generally centered around romantic stories. This is one of them, especially if you can see the genre Western to include Alaska. It is, after all, west as well as north, and this story especially is a very frontier story, even though further north than we usually think of as the frontier.John Wayne plays gold prospector Sam McCord, who with his partner George Pratt (Stewart Granger), have done quite well for themselves on their claim in Alaska. George is eager to get his sweetheart Jennie up to their claim to marry her. She's a French woman living in Seattle. George has even built and furnished a honeymoon cottage for her on their property.So George asks Sam to go to Seattle to fetch her back, which Sam agrees to do. However, when he arrives at what he thinks is her mansion of a home carrying a lot of gifts he bought for her, he is directed to the kitchen. She is not a wealthy woman, she is a maid. She did not believe George would send for her, and she married the butler. Now that George is wealthy, she regrets her choice, but what can she do? More to the point, what can Sam do?Well, he's a resourceful chap, so he goes to a house of entertainment, called the "Hen House," and there he meets Angel (played by French actress Capucine), who is willing to come along to be Jennie's replacement (or perhaps George's consolation prize?). But on the ship on the way there, she falls in love with Sam.One of the best comedy aspects of this story is Fabian in the role of George's teenage brother, who tries to be very adult and sophisticated and get Angel for his own. But Angel is gentle with him, and George is a good sport about the fact that she is not Jennie. When he discovers that she is in love with Sam, he plots with her to hook Sam who was certain he never wanted to be married.It really is a fun story, with a variety of clever sub-plots, including Ernie Kovacs as a hilarious con artist who keeps getting conned himself. The whole thing is played with so much good humor that you won't care that it's not a realistic story altogether. And it's great fun to watch John Wayne play gallant to a prostitute. He does it very well: always the gentleman. Well, sort of. Four stars for the laughs it provided.
summary: John Wayne Had a Lot of Fun With This, and so did the audience

reviewText: This is one of the more 'fun' films of John Wayne (along with Mclintock).  Wayne plays Sam McCord, a prospector who struck it rich in Alaska.  His partner sends him to Seattle to fetch his fiancee, but Sam finds her married and instead goes looking for another French woman (the other woman was French, and Sam apparently thinks all French women are alike).  He finds one, Angel, and takes her to Alaska, but both of them fall in love with the other on the trip back.  The result is a hilarious fiasco of love and hate, with Sam playing the stereotypical stubborn, hardheaded man.This movie is a lot of fun.  There are the typical barroom brawls (as well as a fight on the street), and also a shootout just for good measure.  This is John Wayne through and through, but there is a strong comic element as well.  North to Alaska is definitely worth the time, both for fans of John Wayne and for anyone who enjoys a good, lighthearted western comedy.
summary: A lighthearted film from the Duke

reviewText: After nearly 30 years of playing tough guy roles, John Wayne's star seemed to be fading.  He took on a new role reinventing himself by taking his tough guy image in a comedic and romantic direction.  The result was the highly successful North To Alaska and would set the standard for the rest of John Wayne's ongoing successful career.  The great cast includes Stewart Granger, Capucine, Fabian and the incomparable great television star Ernie Kovacs.  Sit back and enjoy, and be prepared to be thoroughly entertained!
summary: The Film That Re-Invented John Wayne!

reviewText: This movie is based on the characters of George and Sam in the Johnny Horton song, "North to Alaska." John Wayne plays Sam McCord and Stewart Granger the part of George Pratt. The two men follow the lure of gold during the Alaska gold rush after gold was discovered in Nome, which is where the Alaskan action takes place. George in engaged to a woman living in Seattle and after Sam and George strike it rich George sends Sam to Seattle to fetch his fiancé. When Sam discovers that she is married, he finds a substitute woman in a place called "the Hen House" and takes her to Nome.On the way, Sam finds himself developing feelings for her, so when they arrive at their claim, there is friction between Sam and George over the woman and they express it in the proud tradition of the rough and tumble miners, they punch each other. Meanwhile, an unscrupulous scoundrel is able to find a friend of Sam and George's willing to cross file on their claim and all mining operations are put on hold until proper ownership can be established. Sam uses his very direct and unsubtle methods in tracking down the people responsible for their problems over ownership of the mine.This movie casts Wayne in a role that has him being somewhat romantic, although he is not very good at it. It ends with a comedic fight scene that you have to see to be believed, there are many aspects that remind the viewer of the "Three Stooges." It take place in a very muddy street of Nome and has them breaking buildings, one person lands headfirst in a barrel, horned goats getting freed, a seal that claps and then hides its head as Sam punches and gets punched and all with Stooge-like sound effects. It is so silly that it is the perfect capstone to a movie that is a romance executed by a dunce that would rather punch a face than kiss it.
summary: Wayne as a romantic dunce, ridiculous but funny fight scene at the end

reviewText: It is not hard to enjoy this light hearted Western.  John Wayne plays successful Alaskan gold miner Sam McCord.  His partners are the brothers George and Billy Pratt (played, respectively by Stewart Granger and Fabian).  George has just lost the woman he was planning to marry.  Sam is gone to a kind of civilization at a place called "The Hen House".  The women there are more along Sam's type.  A favorite saying of Sam's is that a wife is a woman who concentrates on making one man miserable than a lot of men happy.  But while he is enjoying the company of several lovelies in comes the exotic Michelle (played by the beautiful Capucine), a French woman from New Orleans.Sam decides she would be perfect replacement love for George and invites her to come to Alaska.  During a daylong event with his old lumberjack buddies, Michelle (whom Sam calls Angel) becomes really taken with Sam and gets some signals that he cares for her, too.  Sam passes out from all the beer going around and as she cares for him she finds the two tickets for passage on the boat to Alaska.Well, the whole mess takes off from there and involves more misunderstandings about love, a swindler trying to take the gold mine from the partners (played with wonderful slime by Ernie Kovacs).  Of course, by the end of a movie like this, all mysteries must be solved, all wrongs must be righted, and the right guy has to get the right girl.Enjoy!
summary: John Wayne in a fun Western with a very light heart

reviewText: The great gold rush of the late 1890's brings out thoughts of the wonderful writings of Robert W. Service, and his poems about life during the gold rush.  It's so easy to visualize the John Wayne we see in this movie as being part of Service's writings.Wayne, Stewart Granger, Fabian (???), Capucine and Ernie Kovacs all have major roles, and play them well.  But the supporting cast is equally effective... I don't know the names of the actors, but the characters Mr. and Mrs. Lars Nordquist are terrific.  And Mickey Shaughnessy is perfect as the inebriated miner who once worked the land near Sam McCord's (Wayne) claim.The film is a fun film, intermingled with some nice action.  Some of the scenes seem as if they were copied from photos of the late 1890's.  The scenery is terrific, but don't think that they really went to Alaska to film any of it... it's the best that California could come up with.  The city of Nome is nicely done, right down to the muddy streets.  As you can expect from any John Wayne movie, you'll have a couple of entertaining fights.For those who think of John Wayne as being anti-Indian... forget it.  That is just the opposite of his character in all his films; and is just propoganda uttered by his political foes in an effort to make his feelings less acceptable.  Forget it.  As usual, the only folks Wayne picks on here are the ones who cause the trouble.The whole movie is a romantic fantasy and a very enjoyable one at that.
summary: Great Duke Movie, but would be better on DVD

reviewText: The tremendously entertaining "North to Alaska" is easily John Wayne's most light hearted and fun filled movie and is wonderful viewing for all ages !!Henry Hathaway's lively film is loosely based on the play "Birthday Gift" by Ladislas Fodor and Hathaway shows a wonderful hand in the romantic, comic nature of this film.Confirmed bachelor Wayne and love lorn Grainger strike it rich in Nome, Alaska at the turn of the century and there begins all there problems. Wayne returns to Seattle to bring back Grainger's fiance, finds she has married another man, and ends up in a dance hall and brings back to Nome the glamorous Capucine (she was a knock out in her day !) for Grainger, but the big Duke falls for her womanly charms himself ! Songster Fabian is loads of fun as Grainger's overly amorous kid brother, Billy...and noted funnyman Ernie Kovacs is slick conman Frankie Cannon...eager to get his hands on anyone's fortune. And Johnny Horton's resonant voice sings the title track to the movie !Henry Hathaway often got the best out of the Duke on screen, and if you never thought screen tough guy John Wayne could be funny...see this film...the honeymoon cabin sequence with cunning Grainger and reluctant Capucine stirring up trouble with an irate Wayne listening is simply priceless !Watch closely during the all out brawl in the snow and the mud at the conclusion of the film where Wayne cops a hit on the jaw, falls backwards, and his toupee flies off !Fun, action & romance..."North to Alaska" has got it all !
summary: John Wayne, Stewart Granger & co. shine in Alaskan adventure

reviewText: The best part of this movie made in 1960 is probably the catchy theme song by Johnny Horton which was a big hit around the time this film was released.The only real connection to Alaska is a series of background paintings showing a gold-rush settlement during the credits at the beginning of the film.  Most of the movie looks like a western and was undoubtedly shot at a studio lot in Hollywood.  The beach scenes portraying the gold-rush town of Nome must be from Southern California.  The side trip to Seattle looks like it was filmed in the San Gabriel or San Bernardino mountains north of Los Angeles.  The purported Alaska mountain scenes were probably done in the Sierra Nevada mountain range in eastern California.This is a light romantic Wayne comedy supported by the beautiful French actress Capucine and the 1950s pop star Fabian, who looks ridiculous in his 1950s hairdo in a setting which is supposed to be Alaska around 1900.  The movie portrays the standard Wayne script of battling bad guys but looks out of date today because the definition of bad guys has completely changed.Back then the bad guys were con artists who tried to get ahead by cheating at the expense of society.  Nowadays we have identity politics where the bad guys are whites, men, Christians, and conservatives, unless they can prove otherwise.  Meanwhile today's sacred cows are blacks, Hispanics, homosexuals, and anyone else claiming a victim status.
summary: THE LOST WORLD OF JOHN WAYNE

reviewText: Always known for his tough guy leading man roles, John Wayne takes a stab at a more comedic role with North to Alaska. It's 1900 in Nome and prospectors Sam McCord and George Pratt have struck it big with a claim that's bursting with gold. So with hopes of getting all the gold, McCord goes to Seattle with two goals, buy the necessary equipment and bring back George's fiance of three years. But in Seattle, Sam finds the fiance has married so he finds a different girl, a prostitute named Angel, with hopes of helping his friend out.  But on the way back, Sam and Angel start to fall for each other, arriving back in Nome to find out claim jumpers are moving in.  This was a lot of fun to watch with a storyline that doesn't rush in getting anywhere, letting the characters have fun with the somewhat slim plot.  The scenery is gorgeous, the theme song by Johnny Horton is catchy and will be stuck in your head for awhile,  and the comedic fistfights are well-staged and funny.  If you're a fan of another John Wayne comedy epic, McLintock, give this one a try.In one of his best comedic parts, John Wayne plays Sam McCord, a hard-drinking, fun-loving prospector who strikes it rich. McCord has never had much use for women, but finds himself falling for a woman meant for his friend.  Wayne was an underrated comedian and really seems to be enjoying himself here. Stewart Granger plays George Pratt, McCord's partner who can't wait to see his fiance of so many years. Wayne and Granger's scenes together are some of the highlights in the movie, but much of the supporting cast behind them is disappointing.  International beauty Capucine stars as Angel, Michelle Bonnet, a prostitute in Nome who agrees to travel with McCord back to Nome, but all the while she's hiding something.  Singer Fabian is pretty awkward as Billy Pratt, George's younger brother looking to explore the world, specifically women. Rounding out the leads, Ernie Kovacs is the slimy Frankie Canon, a businessman trying to move in on the town. I guess the cast is okay, but nobody really jumps out here except Granger.The DVD is pretty well put together with a beautiful widescreen presentation that really shows off the filming locations. Special features include a minute long Moviefone clip about the premiere, a North to Alaska trailer, and trailers from The Undefeated and The Comancheros. It's a good DVD to go with a quality comedy with a rare comedic part for John Wayne.  Give North to Alaska a try!
summary: The Duke takes a crack at comedy

It is easy to relate to each of the character roles, and it is one of those films that you want to see more than once.  Also, this film is suitable for the whole family to watch.  The actress "Capucine" plays quite a role.  Recommended film.
